With an imminent IRA statement expected, British and Irish officials are hopeful for a new era in Northern Irish politics.
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams has urged the IRA to embrace democracy and end violence.
Talks between political leaders aim to restore power-sharing institutions.
The Good Friday peace deal of 1998 brought an end to sectarian violence, but concerns remain about paramilitary activities.
The IRA's response to calls for disarmament will be crucial for progress.
Amidst ongoing tensions, the focus is on achieving lasting peace through concrete actions rather than mere words.
